page.title: 01AN AREA N.E. OF DUNNERDALE
page.content: Part if the English Lake District National Park. An extensive upland area with two elevated resevoirs, one on the west flank Seathwaite Tarn and the smaller levers water on the east slope. As part of the conniston fell group the east half of the area is frequented by numerous hill walkers. Noteable summits are Brin Fell, Swirl How, Great Carrs and Grey Friar. Swirl How is the highest point distinctive for its radiated ridges and water drainage to four points of the compass. Panaramic and scenic views abound. Rocky outcrops rough pasture grasses heather cover the area. Sheep grazing land. A few trees exist on the lower north west slopes of Grey Friar and only on that north west tip does a road cut through the area. Habitation is nil although a National Trust Building is used by an Education
